But at last the acrobats came in. A very dull fool stood there with a ladder and made a boy dance from rung to rung and on the very top to the music of popu- lar airs, and then made him hop through burning hoops, and pick up a wine jar with his teeth. No one was excited by this but Trimalchio, who kept saying that it was a thankless profession. There were only two things in the world that he could wateh with real pleasure‚ acrobats and trumpeters3 all other shows were silly nonsense. “Why‚” said he, “1 once bought a Greek comedy company, but I preferred them to do Atellane plays,l and I told my flute-player to have Latin songs.”

Just as Trimalchio was speaking the boy slipped and fell [against his arm]. The slaves raised a cry, and so did the guests, not over a disgusting creature whose neck they would have been glad to see broken, but because it would have been a gloomy finish to the dinner to have to shed tears over the death of a per- fect stranger.
